ops.insert:
I remember a time when I found myself completely in opposition to a universally cast opinion, and this conflict really tested how I work through disagreement and opposing views. It was in the midst of a rather heated debate on personal finance. Many people feel strongly about it, latching on to deeply entrenched beliefs—the one universally accepted in the group was that being a homeowner is better than renting. Everybody was so convinced that buying a home was the ultimate financial goal and the safest investment anyone could ever make. I stood up there and said, "No, that's not true, and here's why."
Flipped by my own research and experiences, I intuitively knew that this was not always true; the idea of the house as an asset and real estate always appreciating was something I learned to question. I read how, in many markets, prices in real estate could stagnate or even lose value and wherein their owners had to face heavy costs of maintenance, taxes, and insurance, moving him away from the benefits if the owner would not live there for long. I concurred with the fact that in some instances paying rent might be a better alternative, combining flexibility in a city instead of purchasing a property. 
The moment I expressed my views, there was an overt tension. It was as if they had been told that a sacred truth had been confronted. Some dismissed my views as naïve and overly cautious. Others sought conversion through family property anecdotes and property value appreciation stories. I knew my views clashed wildly with the crowd's entrenched values.
Following that experience, perhaps my defensiveness deepened for a moment. But it is never easy to swim against the current with a huge, confident majority dominating the waters. Ruminating on this, I avoided tit-for-tat exchanges by listening carefully and reacting calmly. I would often acknowledge their experiences yet present my facts and data. For example, evidence does exist that, in some areas, rent is cheaper than owning when all expenses are taken into consideration. It also speaks to cooling real estate markets over the last few years in many places. I also argued from the standpoint that financial decisions should always be based on individual circumstances rather than broad assumptions. 
What this experience taught me is the importance of distinguishing between opinions and facts. People carry an opinion that feels like a fact because either it is scripted over and over again or it fits into a larger cultural narrative. But, as Robert Kiyosaki and other finance instructors stress, facts, such as numbers and evidence on the ground, need to be taken into consideration when making solid judgments. I noticed when I started focusing on facts rather than emotion and hearsay, things went smoothly; some even admitted that they had never really considered renting as something they could do.
Today, I stand by the belief that you must always consider the potential for argument with an opposing view. I consider it good to respect one another's views and discuss matters calmly. This action reinforces my belief that it is okay to have different opinions, especially if one has valid reasons for them. Sometimes going against the grain might be the right thing to do since standing with the popular may actually cause problems in your life. 
In the end, my view on this issue is that, like so many other financial decisions, whether to rent or buy is an individual one. There is no one single solution. One ought to evaluate one's uniqueness, objectives, and facts rather than gape at so-called popular wisdom. To disagree with the majority is not to have a personal charge; it is being thoughtful and informed.
